caption: Seattle Public Library's Columbia City branch celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2015. The facility has seen a major renovation and the addition of Marvin Oliver's 1992 sculpture "Spirit of Washington."  (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Columbia City is a historic and recently trendy neighborhood in the Rainier Valley in southeast Seattle. (Bettina Hansen/The Seattle Times)

The Columbia City Bakery, on Rainier Avenue South, is a bakery you can bike to and is a recommended detour for people riding along Lake Washington Boulevard in South Seattle.  (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
The former Columbia City Cinema has been reopened as Ark Lodge Cinemas in Columbia City in Seattle.  (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
A runner moves along the circle walk in Bellevue’s Downtown Park. (John Lok / The Seattle Times)
Downtown Bellevue’s Old Main Street is a shopping destination with a traditional style. (Greg Gilbert/The Seattle Times)
Downtown Bellevue is a shopping destination for many and is home to outdoor complexes and large malls, including Bellevue Square. (Steve Ringman / The Seattle Times)
Bellevue Arts Museum, which grew out of an art fair, was founded in 1975. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Moviegoers gather in Capitol Hill’s Cal Anderson Park in 2014 to watch “Dirty Dancing,” presented by Three Dollar Bill Cinema. (Maddie Meyer/The Seattle Times)
The popular Espresso Vivace sidewalk bar on Broadway started as a cart and is now a bit more substantial. (Benjamin Benschneider / The Seattle Times)

One of the few monuments dedicated to the late rocker Jimi Hendrix is a statue on Broadway near Seattle Central College in Seattle. The statue, entitled "The Electric Lady Studio Guitar," was made by artist Daryl Smith.  (John Lok / The Seattle Times)
Everyday Music is a record store across the street from Elliott Bay Book Company on Capitol Hill.   (Sy Bean / The Seattle Times)
Capitol Hill Block Party is a three-day music festival that takes place during the summer. (Sophia Nahli Allison / The Seattle Times)
Admission is free for Frye Art Museum on First Hill. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
St. James Cathedral, the cathedral for the Catholic Archdiocese of Seattle, is on First Hill. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
Opened in 1908, the Sorrento Hotel is a local landmark that has undergone a makeover. The renovation includes this remodeled restaurant, now called the Dunbar Room. (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
Green Lake Park offers a 2.8-mile path for running, biking and walking. On the lake, various clubs have boating events and races. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Runners pass daffodils that bloom along Green Lake trail near Ashworth Avenue North. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
The south end of the lake is home to Green Lake Pitch 'n' Putt, where the longest of the nine 3-par holes is 115 yards. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
From Hiroshima to Hope is an annual event marking the anniversary of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki is held at Green Lake.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
Two large water towers can be seen in the High Point neighborhood of West Seattle. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
The West Seattle Bee Garden is located at the High Point Commons P-Patch. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)

Sunscreens over the windows at Neighborhood House’s High Point Center help reduce energy costs and add beauty to the building that serves families in the area. (Benjamin Benschneider / The Seattle Times)
The commercial strip in "downtown" Lake City offers quite a few options for budget dining, shopping and services. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Matthews Beach on Lake Washington near Lake City is a popular swimming spot in the summer, with great views in any season. (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
The Space Needle casts a shadow over Lower Queen Anne.  (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
Festival-goers enjoy the green space on the Fountain Lawn at Seattle Center in Lower Queen Anne. (Alan Berner / The Seattle Times)
Seattle International Film Festival, known as SIFF, offers shows at the Uptown Cinema. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
Citizen is a mainstay cafe in Lower Queen Anne offering all-day breakfast, including the well-regarded huevos rancheros. (Dean Rutz / The Seattle Times)

The Monorail, built for the World's Fair in 1962, runs a 1-mile route along Fifth Avenue from Seattle Center to Westlake Center. It travels through the Museum of Pop Culture's (formerly EMP) bulbous, colorful building.   (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Skaters were pretty stoked about the course and the views when the skatepark at Beacon Hill's Jefferson Park opened in 2012. (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
PacMed Tower is Beacon Hill defining landmark, and can be seen from much of downtown and surrounding areas.   (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Beacon Hill's Baja Bistro Bar is famous for its chile relleno and Wednesday night Drag Show.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)

Lake Union Wooden Boat Festival is held annually in Seattle at the Center for Wooden Boats. Visitors have access to free ship-building sessions and can tour different kinds of watercraft. (Marcus Yam / The Seattle Times)
The free-to-the public Center for Wooden Boats offers a Sunday Public Sail on South Lake Union.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
Amazon's headquarters are located in the South Lake Union neighborhood of Seattle, stretching into Denny Triangle. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
Seattle Urban Farm Company designed the vegetable and flower gardens on the rooftop deck of the Stackhouse Apartments in South Lake Union.   (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
Boats are moored under University Bridge as Seattle's University District neighborhood rises beyond. (Elaine Thompson / The Associated Press)
The University District Street Fair showcases local arts, music and food. (Alan Berner / The Seattle Times)
Pierce Lane in the University of Washington quad showcases 30 Yoshino cherry trees in their peak beauty for about two weeks every spring.  (Steve Ringman / The Seattle Times)
UW's Suzzallo Library is also referred to as "the Harry Potter library" for its stately gothic interior. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
A view from inside of the beloved Easy Street Records in West Seattle Junction. (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
Shoppers pass by various vendors in the extensive, year-round West Seattle farmer's market. (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
The main strip of West Seattle Junction is a highly walkable area, with shops and services nestled next to each other on California Avenue. (Dean Rutz / The Seattle Times)
A man takes an early morning walk along the shore of Lake Washington in Renton's Gene Coulon Memorial Beach Park. (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
The Landing in Renton, a 46-acre mixed-use development off Interstate 405, is near downtown Renton and offers shopping, dining and fitness options. (Mark Harrison / The Seattle Times)
Seahawks fans shout for Pete Carroll's attention at the annual Seattle Seahawks training camp in Renton. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
The Renton Transit Center is a hub for buses near downtown. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Thousands walk in Renton's Khalsa Day parade. Sikh men, and some women, wear turbans as one of five external articles of faith called the five Kakars. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)

JusMoni dances while DJing at Denny Triangle's Re-bar during Soul Fi, where dance centers around social justice, anti-racism, queerness and "celebrating blackness," said organizer RC Brown. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
It’s the shape of the future as the Amazon “biospheres” come together on Lenora Street between Sixth and Seventh Avenues in Denny Triangle. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)

The Seattle Center Monorail was the nation's first full-scale commercial monorail system and links downtown Seattle to Seattle Center. Here, it travels down the track above Fifth Avenue in Denny Triangle. (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Views from Denny Triangle can be sweeping. Here's the downtown Seattle skyline looking northwest showing the Westin towers, Elliott Bay and the Olympic Mountains. (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
Hale's Brew Pub, next to the Burke-Gilman Trail, is a favorite gathering spot for all ages in Frelard, between Fremont and Ballard. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Frelard Pizza Co. is operated by inventive Seattle restaurateur Ethan Stowell. Geared toward families, it opened in June 2015. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
